  "doc_id": "17922",
  "text": "In the CNS, Gpr126 is expressed by the Bergmann glia of the developing cerebellum, but not on mature oligodendrocytes, which are responsible for myelination [CITATION_1] . However, some PrP C deletion mutants lacking the cleavage site for the N-terminal fragment production also showed severe demyelination in both the spinal cord and cerebellar white matter in vivo [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Thus, although in the CNS an eventual PrP C function in myelin homeostasis is dispensable, a contribution of aberrant PrP C function in demyelinating diseases in the brain is a conceivable scenario. Moreover, whether the N-terminal cleavage product of PrP C is also signaling via other G-protein-coupled receptors in distinct biological processes is likely, but remains to be elucidated.",
